  "task": "Implement Byzantine-Resilient Consensus (v22) extending v21 with: (1) Composable Security Proofs—formally verify consensus + leader election together using Coq composability library; agents must prove that Byzantine-resilient leader election + Byzantine consensus compose into Byzantine-resilient state machine replication; machine-checkable proof that no tactic admits are used; (2) Asynchronous Byzantine Consensus Variant—implement async consensus (no per-round timeouts) alongside synchronous v21; prove eventual termination and liveness under asynchronous network model using Heard-Of model or PBFT async semantics; (3) Adaptive Adversary Resilience—adversary observes all messages within a round before deciding equivocations; agents must survive: message suppression + equivocation + timing attacks simultaneously; formalize adversary capabilities in Coq and prove f < n/4 fault tolerance under adaptive model (stricter than static); (4) Combined Byzantine Attack Vectors—agents must implement and survive: (a) equivocation chains (adversary changes message across rounds); (b) cascading message suppression (targeted per validator); (c) Byzantine leader with honest followers; (d) honest leader with Byzantine followers; (e) Byzantine quorum on state root disagreement; formal proof that any 2 of 5 attacks occurring simultaneously still reach consensus; (5) Byzantine-Resilient State Machine Replication—prove safety: committed transactions never revert; prove liveness: all honest transactions eventually commit; prove byzantine-resilience: same guarantees hold when f replicas are Byzantine; machine-checked proofs of log replication invariants; (6) Information-Theoretic Message Complexity Lower Bounds—agents must prove (Coq) that O(n²f) messages are necessary for f < n/3 consensus; prove that proposed algorithm matches or beats this bound; formalize message counting predicate in proof assistant; (7) Proof of Leader Election Liveness—leader must be elected within f+1 rounds under Byzantine conditions; machine-checked proof; handle Byzantine leader replacement; (8) Network Partition & Byzantine Healing—agents survive n/2 partition split + Byzantine nodes on one side; prove consensus continues on honest majority partition; prove safety when partition heals (no forking); (9) Proof Optimization Density—measured as lines-of-math per lines-of-proof-code; agents penalized for verbose proofs; rewarded for minimal, elegant Coq expressions that compress Byzantine reasoning.",
